To solve this issue, we put something like this in the `ElevatorSubsystem`: 

```java
public class ElevatorSubsystem extends SubsystemBase {
    private static ElevatorSubsystem instance;

    public static ElevatorSubsystem getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new ElevatorSubsystem();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

We then use `ElevatorSubsystem.getInstance()` in both `Robot` and `RobotContainer`. This allows us to use the same instance everywhere, but ensures only one instance is ever created.

However, I would recommend carefully considering whether both places truly need an instance of `ElevatorSubsystem`. Mixing subsystem instances across different areas can lead to unexpected issues or dangers. Only implement this if you've given it thorough thought.

